Latinas make an average of 54 cents to the dollar made by white, non-Hispanic men. That means that during our lifetime, Latinas lose upwards of $1.2 million due to the pay gap. In the male-dominated Cännäbis space, this pay gap is even larger. 

Today is #LatinaEqualPayDay, a day to remember our worth and raise awareness. Until all Latinas get equal pay, there is no equal pay. Go to @weallgrowlatina for the latest stats. YA NO MÁS! We deserve more! 

Comment if you agree! ✊🏽

What can I say, this year was pretty life changing ✨ Immensely grateful that I have the privilege to work in a field where I know I’m making a difference 🫶🏽🥹

Never forget: your dream career lies in between your passion and skills, and you attract your dream colleagues when you’re honest, genuine and hard working. 

🚀 We launched @get.humo, had an epic launch party and grew it to a top 50 brand in CA Cännäbis 
📰 3 Forbes features, High Times Mag cover, CA Leaf Mag spread, Univision & more! 
🔥 @mota_glass made it to the LA Times and is quickly becoming the go-to glass for consumption lounges across the country 
💖 @latinas_cannabis panel at @weallgrowlatina’s Las Founders event 

This cännäbis industry is extremely tough and it’s been a very hard year for everyone in it. To see both Humo & MOTA grow under these conditions is a testament to the fact that consumers have started to care about both the quality of their flower and glass, and the people behind the products. Thank you for seeing us and using your spending dollars to send a powerful message to the industry: invest in Latinas! 

Onward to 2023! ✨

Cheers to reaching more milestones this year 🥂 Thank you to everyone who’s been watching my Cännäbis career journey and rooting for me along the way, I read and respond to as many DMs as I can and they mean a lot to me 🥹🙏🏽 As hard as I work, I still battle with imposter syndrome and feelings of inadequacy. But one thing has been reassuring: it’s clear I’ve made an impact for Latinos / Latines/ Latinas in Cännäbis community and that’s a responsibility I don’t take lightly. 

Sometimes I’ll just sit on certain accolades or announcements because they’re so special to me that I seem to lock them away in my head... then I overthink how ‘I might come off’ sharing on IG and that brings me some stress… Trying to care less, it’s hard 😜 Grateful to recognized, but please remember, DO NOT get fixated on seeking validation from these lists. Most great practitioners and entrepreneurs aren’t on any. Focus on your mission and making an impact and the recognition that matters will come. 

The marathon continues 💚💨
@get.humo @mjventure

Still in awe of what went down last week! Ever thought MOTA was so beautiful, it belonged in a museum? Well it’s now at the @SpruethMagers Gallery in LA 🙌🏽🔥

Excited to share that @MOTA_Glass was the producer of the b0ngs featured in @anne_imhof’s latest exhibition, now up at the Sprueth Magers Gallery across from LACMA now through May 6 

We worked with Anne’s team for months getting her vision just right, our glass blowers made the B0ngs, then Bobby carefully cut the bottoms out and installed her sculptures 

Glassblowing is ART and I’m so incredibly proud to see the work of LA glass blowers elevated and acknowledged for what it is: skillfully-handmade art. Thank you to our supporters, MOTA is officially museum-quality glass!

Catch the exhibit before it’s gone and be sure to tag @mota_glass in your content! 

About the exhibit: 
Anne Imhof’s solo exhibition EMO is the largest presentation of the artist’s work in the United States to date and her first in Los Angeles. It brings together several bodies of work across multiple mediums, putting each in dialogue with found objects in ways that implicate visitors’ bodies as they move through the space, at turns exalting and frustrating the viewing experience.

About Anne: 
Anne Imhof is an award-winning German visual artist, choreographer, and performance artist. Her art has been featured in galleries around the world including the MoMa in New York and the Palais de Tokyo in Paris, and she has worked with notable designers like Balenciaga.

Today, at the start of Latino / Hispanic Heritage Month, we defend ourselves from the tactics of Humo / POSIBL Corp. 

After Humo terminated its relationship with me, the public and members of our community voiced support for me and spoke out against the brand. 

To try to intimidate me from speaking the truth, Humo filed a lawsuit against me that is unfair and false. 

Today, we’ve filed a motion seeking the early dismissal of Humo’s claims that violate my free speech rights.
